  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and around me. Growing up in Rome with parents who had different educational backgrounds—my dad finished upper secondary, my mom a bachelor's degree—my early exposure to science was limited. I remember being handed a math textbook at age 12, but the way it was presented felt alien. I wasn't the type to get frustrated by it, but I did feel like I was being judged for not 'getting it' quickly. That's when I started noticing how people's expectations about who belongs in STEM could shape your performance. For instance, when I was delivering packages in Rome, I often saw women and minorities in tech roles, but their confidence was sometimes undermined by assumptions about their capabilities. I've heard stories from friends who dropped out of STEM programs because they felt like they weren't 'meant' to be there. This isn't just about individual failure—it's systemic. The question of whether we should address it is clear: yes, absolutely. But the way we do it matters. Instead of just telling people 'you can do it,' we need to create environments where everyone feels safe to make mistakes. In my community, this means supporting mentorship programs that pair students with role models who look like them, not just in STEM but in everyday contexts. It's about shifting the narrative from 'you have to be perfect' to 'you're valued for your unique perspective.' And since I'm curious about how this affects different groups, I'd love to see more inclusive practices in schools and workplaces. The key is to make STEM feel accessible, not intimidating, so that anyone who wants to learn can do so without fear.",
